sections.introduction:
Let ${\mathbb F}_q$ be a finite field with $q$ elements, ${{\mathbb F}}^*_q$ be its  multiplicative group, ${\mathbb F}^n_q$ be  a set of vectors of length  $n$ over ${{\mathbb F}}_q$ . Any non-empty set $C\subseteq{\mathbb F}^n_q$ is called a code of length $n$ over ${{\mathbb F}}_q$. If $C$ is a linear subspace over ${\mathbb F}_q$, then the code $C$ is called \textit{linear code}.

A component-wise product of vectors $v=(v_1,v_2,\dots ,v_n)$ and  $w=(w_1,$$w_2,$$\dots,$$w_n)$ is defined as $v\circ w=(v_1w_1,v_2w_2,\dots ,v_nw_n)$. For vectors $v=(v_1,v_2,\dots ,v_n)\in {{\mathbb F}}^n_q$, $c=(c_1,c_2,\dots ,c_n)\in {\left({{\mathbb F}}^*_q\right)}^n$,  and a permutation $\pi =\left( \begin{array}{c}
1 \\ 
\pi \left(1\right)\  \end{array}
 \begin{array}{c}
2 \\ 
\pi \left(2\right)\  \end{array}
 \begin{array}{c}
\dots  \\ 
\dots  \end{array}
 \begin{array}{c}
\ n \\ 
\ \pi (n) \end{array}
\right)$  
on the set $I_n=\{1, 2,\dots , n\}$($\pi $ is an element of the symmetric group  $S_n$ on $n$ elements) we define the following vectors:
$v^{\pi}=(v_{\pi(1)},v_{\pi(2)},\dots ,v_{\pi(n)})$ is a permutation of components of vector $v$ under the action of $\pi$;
$v^{(\pi, c)}=(c_1 v_{\pi(1)}, c_2 v_{\pi(2)},\dots , c_n v_{\pi(n)})$ is a result of transformation  $(\pi , c)$ on $v$.

Notice, that $(v^{\pi })^{\rho}=v^{\pi \rho}$ and $\left(v^{(\pi, a)}\right)^{(\rho, b)}=(v^{\pi }\circ a)^{(\rho, b)}=v^{\pi \rho }\circ a^{\rho }\circ b=v^{\pi \rho}\circ a^{(\rho, b)}$, where $\pi \rho $ is a product of permutations $\pi $ and $\rho $ with multiplication on the left, that is $\pi \rho(x)=\pi(\rho(x))$, $x\in I_n$.

For a code $V \subseteq{{\mathbb F}}^n_q$, $\pi \in S_n$, $c\in {\left({{\mathbb F}}^*_q\right)}^n$ we set
\[V^{\pi }=\left\{v^{\pi }|v\in V\right\}, 
V\circ c=\left\{v\circ c|v\in V\right\}, 
V^{(\pi ,c)}=V^{\pi }\circ c=\left\{v^{(\pi ,c)}|v\in V\right\}.\] 
A transformation $(\pi ,\ c)$, preserving the code $V$(that is $V^{(\pi ,c)}=V$), is called a \textit{monomial automorphism} of the code $V$. A set ${\rm MAut}(V)$ of all such automorphisms forms  a group with multiplication (on the left): 
\[\left(\rho ,b\right)\times \left(\pi ,a\right)=(\pi \rho ,\ a^{(\rho ,b)}).\]
Let us  define the following groups:
\[{\rm Sym}\left(V\right)=\{(\pi ,\ {\mathbf 1})|(\pi ,\ {\mathbf 1})\in {\rm MAut}(V)\},\] 
where ${\mathbf 1}=(1,1,\dots ,1)$ is a vector consisting of  identity elements of the field ${{\mathbb F}}_q$;
\[{\rm P}\left(V\right)=\{\pi |(\pi ,\ c)\in {\rm MAut}(V)\}.\]${\rm Sym}\left(V\right)$ is  a  group of symmetry, ${\rm P}\left(V\right)$ is a group of permutations of the code $V$.  If $V$ is a binary code,   $q=2$, and  ${{\mathbb F}}_q$ is a field of two elements, then  ${\rm Sym}\left(V\right)={\rm MAut}(V)$. These groups differ  only when  $q>2$.


The codes $V_1$ and $V_2$ are called \textit{equivalent} if there  exists some transformation $\left(\rho ,a\right)$ such that $V_2=V^{\left(\rho ,a\right)}_1$. Notice, that for linear codes the transition to an equivalent code means a permutation of columns of the code's generator matrix  and then  multiplying its columns by some non-zero elements of the field ${{\mathbb F}}_q$. The equivalent codes $V_1$ and $V_2$ have isomorphic automorphism groups. It is not difficult to  establish that
\[(\pi ,\ c)\in {\rm MAut}(V_1)\Leftrightarrow (\tau ,\ b)\in {\rm MAut}(V_2),\] 
where $\tau ={\rho }^{-1}\ \pi \rho $ for some permutation $\rho \in S_n$, $b={{(a}^{-1}{\rm )}}^{\tau }\circ c^{(\rho ,a)}$, $a^{-1}=(a^{-1}_1,a^{-1}_2,\dots ,a^{-1}_n)$ for $a=(a_1,a_2,\dots ,a_n)$. Such correspondence establishes the isomorphism of groups     ${\rm MAut}(V_1)$ and  ${\rm M}{\rm A}{\rm ut}(V_2)$. In particular, if  ${V_2=V}_1\circ a$, then $P(V_2)=P(V_1)$ and

\begin{equation}\label{eq1}
{\rm MAut}(V_2)=\{(\pi ,\ {(a^{-1})}^{\pi }\circ c\circ a)|(\pi , c)\in {\rm MAut}(V_1)\}. \end{equation}
Notice also the following fact: if $V$ is a linear code such that its generator matrix consists of a single row $g=(g_1,g_2,\dots ,g_n)\in {\left({{\mathbb F}}^*_q\right)}^n$, then

\begin{equation*}\label{eq2}
{\rm MAut}(V)=\{(\pi ,\ c)\,|\,c=e\ (g^{-1})^{\pi }\circ g,\ \pi \in S_n,e\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q\}.\end{equation*}\begin{lemma}\label{lemma1} Let $V \in  {{\mathbb F}}^n_q$ be a linear code, $V^{\bot }$ be its dual code, $e\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q$. Then
\begin{equation}\label{eq3}(\pi ,\ c)\in {\rm MAut}\left(V\right)\Longleftrightarrow (\pi ,\ ec)\in {\rm MAut}\left(V\right),\end{equation}  
\begin{equation}\label{eq4}{\rm MAut}\left(V^{\bot }\right)=\{(\pi ,\ {a}^{-1})|(\pi ,\ a)\in {\rm MAut}(V)\}.\end{equation}
\end{lemma}\begin{proof} The property  (\ref{eq3}) is evident. Let $v=(v_1,v_2,\dots ,v_n)\in V$, $w=(w_1,w_2,\dots ,w_n)$ $\in $ $ V^{\bot }$ , $v\cdot w=v_1w_1+v_2w_2+\dots +v_nw_n$ be an inner product of vectors  $v$ and $w$.  Since $v^{(\pi, a)}\cdot w^{(\pi, a^{-1})}$ $=$ $\ v\cdot w=0$, then  $V^{(\pi,a)}$ and ${(V^{\bot })}^{(\pi, a^{-1})}$ are dual codes. In other words, $\left(\pi, a\right)\in {\rm MAut}\left(V\right)$ iff $\left(\pi, a^{-1}\right)\in {\rm MAut}\left(V^{\bot }\right)$. \end{proof}
Let $V_1$,\dots , $V_m\subseteq{{\mathbb F}}^n_q$ be linear codes. We denote by  ${V=V}_1\circ \dots \circ V_m$ a linear subspace over  ${{\mathbb F}}_q$, which is  spanned by vectors ${v=v}_1\circ \dots \circ v_m$, $v_1\in V_1$,\dots ,$\ v_m\in V_m$.  We call $V$\textit{component-wise product  of codes}$V_1$,\dots , $V_m$.


\begin{lemma}\label{lemma2} Let $V_1$,\dots , $V_m\subseteq{{\mathbb F}}^n_q$ be linear codes, $(\pi, c_i)\in {\rm MAut}\left(V_i\right)$, $i=1,\dots ,n$. Then 
\[(\pi, c_1\circ \dots \circ c_m)\in {\rm MAut}\left(V_1\circ \dots \circ V_m\right).\] 
\end{lemma}\begin{proof} If $v_1\in V_1$,\dots ,$\ v_m\in V_m$, then ${\left(v_1\circ \dots \circ v_m\right)}^{\left(\pi, {c}_1\circ \dots \circ c_m\right)}={v_1}^{\left(\pi, c_1\right)}\circ \dots \circ{v_m}^{\left(\pi, {c}_m\right)}\in V_1\circ \dots \circ V_m$. \end{proof}
A Reed--Solomon code ${RS}_{t,q}$($1\leq t \leq q-3$) is defined  as a linear code of  length $n=q-1$ with a generator matrix 
\[G_{t,q}=\left( \begin{array}{ccc}
 \begin{array}{ccc}
1\  & 1 & 1 \\ 
1\  & \alpha^1 & \alpha^2 \\ 
1\  & \alpha^2 & \alpha^4 \end{array}
 & \cdots  &  \begin{array}{c}
1 \\ 
\alpha^{q-2} \\ 
\alpha^{2(q-2)} \end{array}
 \\ 
\vdots  & \ddots  & \vdots  \\ 
 \begin{array}{ccc}
1 & \alpha^t & \alpha^{t2} \end{array}
 & \cdots  & \alpha^{t(q-2)} \end{array}
\right),\] 
where $\alpha$ is the primitive  element  of the field ${{\mathbb F}}_q$. Notice, that the code $V=RS_{t,q}$, where $t=q-2$, consists of all possible vectors over  ${\mathbb F}_q$ such that length of these vectors is $q-1$, that is $V= {{\mathbb F}}^{q-1}_q$. The distance of this code is equal to 1, so there is no interest for investigation of this code.  For this code we have that $ {\rm MAut}\cong S_{q-1}\times({{\mathbb F}}^*_q)^{q-1}$ is a group of order $(q-1)!(q-1)^{q-1}.$ This explains the restriction $t\leq q-3.$
Extensions \footnote{Here  a term ``extending'' a code means the increasing the length of code vectors by adding some extra columns to a generator matrix of the code.}${RS}^e_{t,q}$, ${RS}^{2e}_{t,q}$, and ${RS}^{3e}_{t,q}$ of the code  ${RS}_{t,q}$ by adding one, two, and three symbols respectively are  defined  as linear codes over ${{\mathbb F}}_q$ of length  $n=q$, $n=q+1$, and $n=q+2$ respectively. Generator matrices of these codes are 
\[G^e_{t,q}=\left(e_0|G_{t,q}\right), G^{2e}_{t,q}=\left(G^e_{t,q}|{{\rm e}}_{{\rm 1}}\right), G^{3e}_{t,q}=\left(G^{2e}_{t,q}|{{\rm e}}_{{\rm 2}}\right),\] 
where $e_0={\left(1,\ 0,\dots ,\ 0\right)}^T$, $e_1={\left(\ 0,\dots ,\ 0,\ 1\right)}^T$, $e_2={\left(0,\ \dots ,\ 0,\ 1,\ 0\right)}^T$ are the columns with $t+1$ elements. Their dual codes are
\[{RS}^{\bot }_{t,q}={RS}_{q-3-t,q}\circ (1,\ \alpha ,\ {\alpha }^2,\dots ,\ {\alpha }^{q-2})\](in other words, a generator matrix of the code ${RS}^{\bot }_{t,q}$ is constructed from $G_{q-2-t,q}$ by deleting the first row, which contains only one's);


\begin{equation}\label{eq5}
{({RS}^e_{t,q})}^{\bot }={RS}^e_{q-2-t,q},
{({RS}^{2e}_{t,q})}^{\bot }={RS}^{2e}_{q-1-t,q},
\end{equation}\begin{equation*}\label{eq7}
{({RS}^{3e}_{t,q})}^{\bot }={({RS}^{3e}_{q-t,q})}^{\tau },\ 2\le t\le q-2,
\end{equation*}%
where $\tau $ is a permutation of two last columns in the generator matrix. Thus dual codes are either  $RS$-codes or are equivalent to  them. 


Codes ${RS}_{t,q}$,$\ {RS}^e_{t,q}$, ${RS}^{2e}_{t,q}$,  ${RS}^{3e}_{2,2^m}$, and ${RS}^{3e}_{2^m-2,2^m}$ belong to a class of so  called Maximum
Distance Separable (MDS) codes, which lies on the Singleton bound \cite[\S 1.10]{MVC79}. Such codes possess   many remarkable properties and  many other codes are being constructed on their base.

A common description of monomial automorphism  groups of the codes ${RS}_{t,q}$, ${RS}^e_{t,q}$, ${RS}^{2e}_{t,q}$ is given in  \cite{D87}, where it is shown that
\[P\left({RS}_{t,q}\right)\cong D_{q-1}, 
P\left({RS}^e_{t,q}\right)\cong{\rm Aff}(1,{\mathbb F}_q), 
P\left({RS}^{2e}_{t,q}\right)\cong{\rm PGL}(2,{\mathbb F}_q),\] 
where $D_{q-1}$ is a Dihedral group of transformations $z\rightarrow \alpha z,\ \ z\rightarrow \frac{1}{z}\ $ that acts on the set ${{\mathbb F}}^*_q;$${\rm Aff}\left(1,\ {{\mathbb F}}_q\right)$ is an affine group of transformations   $z\rightarrow az+b,\ a\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q$, $b\in {{\mathbb F}}_q$ on the set  ${{\mathbb F}}_q;$${\rm PGL}(2,\ {{\mathbb F}}_q)$ is a group of linear fractional transformations  $z\rightarrow \cfrac{az+b}{cz+d}$ on the set ${{\mathbb F}}_q\cup \left\{\infty \right\}. $ These automorphism groups, which are called generalized automorphisms, are pointed by Sidelnikov in \cite{S08}, where he remarked that full automorphism groups of codes ${RS}^e_{t,q}$, ${RS}^{2e}_{t,q}$ are unknown. In this paper we calculate the explicit  transformations (determined by polynomials over the field ${{\mathbb F}}_q$), which constitute the full monomial automorphism  groups for the codes mentioned   above: in Section 2 we consider codes $RS_{t,q}$ and $R^e_{t,q}$, in Section 3 we consider codes $RS^{2e}_{t,q}$. We show (Section 4) that codes $RS^{2e}_{t,q}$ are equivalent to constacyclic codes and, when $tq$ is even, to cyclic codes.  Finally, in Section 5, we calculate the full automorphism groups of codes $RS^{3e}_{2,2^m}$ and $RS^{3e}_{2^m-2,2^m}$, which are MDS-extensions of codes $RS_{t,q}$ on three symbols.  This work continues the investigation of one of the authors  \cite{K77,K78,Ku78,K93}, where the full groups of symmetry  $Sym(V)$ are calculated for several classes of linear cyclic codes.

main_part:
\label{section_2}
For shortness, we call a linear cyclic code  $V\subseteq{{\mathbb F}}^n_q$$C(n,q)$-code. In this section we consider only codes of  primitive length $n=q-1$ and their extensions to length $n+1=q$ by adding overall parity check.

A generator matrix of $C\left(q-1,q\right)$-code $V$ has the form
\[G=\left( \begin{array}{ccc}
 \begin{array}{ccc}
1 & {\alpha }^{i_1} & {\alpha }^{{2i}_1} \end{array}
 & \cdots  & {\alpha }^{{(q-2)i}_1} \\ 
\vdots  & \ddots  & \vdots  \\ 
 \begin{array}{ccc}
1 & {\alpha }^{i_k} & {\alpha }^{{2i}_k} \end{array}
 & \cdots  & {\alpha }^{{(q-2)i}_k} \end{array}
\right),\] 
where ${\alpha }^{i_1}$,\dots , ${\alpha }^{i_k}\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q$ are different elements.  A generator polynomial of the code $V$ is  $\left(x^n-1\right)/(x^kh\left(x^{-1}\right))$, where $h(x)=\left(x-{\alpha }^{i_1}\right)\dots \left(x-{\alpha }^{i_k}\right)$. The matrix $G$ is a  parity-check matrix for the dual code $V^{\bot }$ with the generator polynomial $h(x)$.


We will enumerate the components of codewords by elements of the set ${{\mathbb F}}^*_q=\{{\alpha }^0$, ${\alpha }^1$\dots , ${\alpha }^{q-2}\}$. The following two sets are associated with the code $V$:
\[J_V=\{i_1,\dots ,\ i_k\}, \]\[{\Omega }_V=\left\{\delta (x)|\delta (x)=\sum_{j\in J_V}{{\delta }_jx^j}\in {{\mathbb F}}_q\left[x\right]\right\}.\]
Then an arbitrary code vector $v=(v_{{\alpha }^0},v_{{\alpha }^1},\dots ,v_{{\alpha }^{q-2}})\in V$ can be defined as 
\[v=v\left(\delta (x)\right)=\left(\delta(\alpha^0),\delta(\alpha^1),\dots ,\delta(\alpha^{q-2})\right)\] 
for some  $\delta (x)\in {\Omega }_V$ and the code $V$ can be determined as 
\[V=\{v\left(\delta (x)\right)|\delta (x)\in {\Omega }_V\}.\]
Notice, that for the dual code $V^{\bot }$\[J_{V^{\bot}}=\left\{0,\ 1,\dots ,\ q-2\right\}\backslash \{{\left\lfloor -i_1\right\rfloor }_{q-1},\dots ,{\left\lfloor -i_k\right\rfloor }_{q-1}\},\] 
where ${\left\lfloor j\right\rfloor }_n$ is the least  nonnegative residue of the number   $j$ by modulo $n.\ $ An extension $V^e$ of the code $V$ is determined as a set of vectors
\[v^e=v^e\left(\delta(x)\right)=\left(\delta(0),\delta(\alpha^0),\delta(\alpha^1),\dots ,\delta(\alpha^{q-2})\right),\ \ \delta(x)\in {\Omega }_V,\] 
of length $q$(i.e. vectors $v(\delta(x))\in V$ are extended by adding a new component with the value $\delta(0)$). If $0\notin J_V$, then  $\delta\left(0\right)\equiv 0$. Therefore the extension  $V^e$ is nontrivial  if  $0\in J_V$ and the generator matrix of the code $V$ has the row with all elements equal 1.


Automorphisms $(\pi,c)$ of  $C\left(q-1,q\right)$-code $V$ can be defined by polynomials  $\pi(x)$, $c(x)\in {{\mathbb F}}_q\left[x\right]$, where $\pi(x)$ is a permutation polynomial of the set  ${{\mathbb F}}^*_q$, for which the mapping  ${{\mathbb F}}^*_q\longrightarrow{{\mathbb F}}^*_q$, $x\longmapsto \pi(x)$ is a bijection, and $c(x)$ is a polynomial that does not have any roots in ${{\mathbb F}}^*_q.$ Since polynomials $\pi(x)$ and $\pi(x)+a(x)\sigma(x)$($\sigma(x)=x^{q-1}-1$) determine the same mapping on ${{\mathbb F}}^*_q$, then we have that degree ${\deg \pi(x)\ }$ of the polynomial  $\pi(x)$ does not exceed ${\deg \sigma(x)\ }-1=q-2\ $. The same remark  also holds for the polynomial  $c(x)$.

The automorphisms of the code $V^e$  can be defined by the similar way  (with substitution ${{\mathbb F}}_q$ for ${{\mathbb F}}^*_q$ and $\sigma(x)=x^q-x$ for $\sigma(x)=x^{q-1}-1$).

Let $J_1$,\dots ,$\ J_m$ be subsets of the set $\left\{0,\ 1,\dots ,q-2\right\}$. Denote by $J_1+\dots +J_m\ ({\rm mod}\ q-1)$ a set  of integers $0\le j\le q-2$ that can be represented as  $j\equiv j_1+\dots +j_m\ ({\rm mod}\ q-1)$, $j_1\in J_1$,\dots , $j_m\in J_m$.

The following statement is a particular case of Theorem 1 from  \cite{K75} in respect to component-wise product of semi-simple  $C(n,q)$-codes, for which $\gcd(n,q)=1$.

\begin{lemma}\label{lemma3}If $V_1$,..., $V_m\subseteq{{\mathbb F}}^{q-1}_q$ are $C(q-1,\ q)$-codes, then $V=V_1\circ \dots \circ V_m$ also is $C(q-1,\ q)$-code and  $J_V=J_{V_1}+\dots +J_{V_m}({\rm mod}\ q-1)$.  
\end{lemma}\begin{proof} Vectors  $g^{(j)}=(1,$ $\alpha^j,$ $\alpha^{2j},\dots,$ $\alpha^{(q-2)j})$,  $j\in J_{V_i}$, $i=1,\dots \ ,m$ form a basis for the code $V_i$. Then linear combinations of vectors $g^{(j)}=(1,\alpha^j,$ $\alpha^{2j},$ $\dots,$ $\alpha^{(q-2)j})$ over  ${{\mathbb F}}_q$, where $0\le j\le q-2$, $j\equiv j_1+\dots +j_m\ ({\rm mod}\ q-1)$, $j_1\in J_{V_1}$,\dots , $j_m\in J_{V_m}$ form the code  $V$.\end{proof}
The following lemma gives a  description of groups ${\rm MAut}\left(V\right)$ and ${\rm MAut}(V^e)$ for an arbitrary $C(q-1,\ q)$-code $V$.

\begin{lemma}\label{lemma4} Let $V$ be $C(q-1,\ q)$-code, $W=V$ or $W=V^e$; $F={{\mathbb F}}^*_q$ or $F={{\mathbb F}}_q$ correspondingly to the cases  $W=V$ or $W=V^e$; $\pi(x)\in {{\mathbb F}}_q[x]$ be a permutation polynomial of the set  $F$,  $c(x)\in {{\mathbb F}}_q[x]$ be a polynomial that does not have any roots in $F$. Then $(\pi(x),c(x))\in {\rm MAut}\left(W\right)$ iff

\begin{equation}\label{eq8}
{c(x) \pi(x)}^j({\rm mod}{\rm \ }\sigma(x))\in {\Omega }_V \mbox{ for each }j\in J_V,\end{equation}
%
where $\sigma(x)=x^{q-1}-1$ or $x^q-x$ correspondingly for $W=V$ and $W=V^e$,  $\psi(x)\ {\rm mod\ }\sigma(x)$ is a residue of division  $\psi(x)$ by $\sigma(x)$.
\end{lemma}\begin{proof} Denote by  $w(a(x))$ a vector $v(a(x))$ or $v^e(a(x))$ correspondingly for the cases $W=V$ or $W=V^e$. Then there exists some vector $w(x^j)$ that corresponds to the polynomial  $x^j$, where $j\in J_V$. Under the action of automorphism $(\pi(x),\ c(x))$ this vector transforms to the vector  $w({c(x)\cdot \pi(x)}^j)\in W$. So $w({c(x)\cdot \pi(x)}^j)=w(\delta(x))$ for some  $\delta(x)\in {\Omega }_V$. Because ${c(\xi)\cdot \pi(\xi)}^j$=$\delta(\xi)$ for each $\xi \in F$ then ${c(x)\cdot \pi (x)}^j({\rm mod\ }\sigma (x))=\delta (x)$.

Conversely, if relation  (\ref{eq8}) holds, then the  transformation $(\pi(x),\ c(x))$ converts vectors $w(x^j)$, which form the basis of $W$, to vectors that also belong to $W$. In other words, $(\pi(x), c(x))\in {\rm MAut}(W)$. \end{proof}\begin{lemma}\label{lemma5} Let $J_V=\{t\}$, where $0\le t\le q-2$. Then 
\[{\rm MAut}\left(V\right)=\left\{\left(\pi (x), c(x)\right)|\pi (x)\in S\left({{\mathbb F}}^*_q\right),\ c(x)=\frac{ax}{{\pi (x)}^t},\ a\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q\right\},\] 
where $S\left({{\mathbb F}}^*_q\right)$ is a set of permutation polynomials  for ${{\mathbb F}}^*_q$ (symmetric group of permutations on elements of the set ${{\mathbb F}}^*_q$ that defines by polynomials).
\end{lemma}\begin{proof} Let $(\pi (x),\ c(x))\in {\rm MAut}\left(V\right)$. A generator matrix  of the code $V$ consists of a single row $g=(1$, ${\alpha }^t$, $\alpha^{2t},$\dots , ${\alpha }^{(q-2)t}).$ Obviously, that  $P(V)=S\left({\mathbb F}^*_q\right)$. Because ${\Omega }_V=\left\{ax^t|a\in {{\mathbb F}}_q\right\}$ then  from Lemma \ref{lemma4} it follows that ${c(x)\cdot \pi (x)}^t=ax^t$ for each $x=\xi \in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q$ and for some $a\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q$. This implies that  $c(x)=\cfrac{ax^t}{\pi(x)^t}.$ \end{proof}\begin{lemma}\label{lemma6} Let $U$ and $V$  be $C(q-1,\ q)$-codes such that  $J_V=J_U+\{m\}$, where $m$ is an arbitrary integer. Then  $P(V)=P(U)$.
\end{lemma}\begin{proof} The claim directly follows  from relation (\ref{eq1}) because $V=U\circ a$ when  $a=(1,\alpha^m, \alpha^{2m}, \dots, \alpha^{(q-2)m})$. \end{proof}\begin{lemma}\label{lemma7} Let $q>2$. Then  
\[{\rm MAut}\left({RS}_{1,q}\right)=\{\left(bx,c\right),\left(bx^{q-2},cx\right)|b,c\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q\}.\]
\end{lemma}\begin{proof} The code ${RS}_{1,q}$ is a  $C(q-1,\ q)$-code, for which $J_V=\{0,\ 1\}$, ${\Omega }_V=\{{\delta }_1x+{\delta }_0|{\delta }_0,{\delta }_1\in {{\mathbb F}}_q\}$. Let $(\pi (x),\ c(x))\in {\rm MAut}\left({RS}_{1,q}\right)$. According to Lemma \ref{lemma4} we have that polynomials  $\pi (x)$ and $c(x)$ satisfy to the following relations:

\begin{equation}\label{eq9}
{c(x)\cdot \ \pi (x)}^j({\rm mod}{\rm \ }x^{q-1}-1)\in {\Omega }_V, \ j=0,1. \end{equation}


From (\ref{eq9}), using $j=0$, we have that $c(x)=c_1x+c_0$. Because $c\left(\xi \right)\ne 0$ for any $\xi \in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q$ then $c_0\cdot c_1=0$ and  consequently $c(x)=c_0$ or $c(x)=c_1x$, $c_0,c_1\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q$. From the next chain of equations 

\[0=\sum_{\beta \in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q}{\beta }=\sum_{\beta \in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q}{\pi (\beta )}={\pi }_0\sum_{\beta \in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q}{1}+\sum^{q-2}_{i=1}{{\pi }_i}\sum_{\beta \in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q}{{\beta }^i=}{\pi }_0\left(q-1\right),\] 
%
which holds for the polynomial $\pi (x)={\pi }_0+{\pi }_1x+\dots +{\pi }_{q-2}x^{q-2}$, it follows  that ${\pi }_0=0$. But then from  equation (\ref{eq9}), using  $j=1$, we have that $\pi (x)=bx$ and $bx^{q-2}=bx^{-1}$, $b\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q$ respectively for  $c(x)=c_0$ and $c(x)=c_1x$. \end{proof}\begin{theorem}\label{thm8} Let $V={RS}_{t,q}$, $0\le t\le q-3$. Then 

\begin{equation}\label{eq10}
P\left(V\right)=D_{q-1}=\{bx, bx^{q-2}\,|\,b\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q\}
\end{equation}
%
is a dihedral group of  order  $2(q-1)$;

\begin{equation}\label{eq11}
{\rm MAut}\left({RS}_{t,q}\right)=\{(bx,c), (bx^{q-2},cx^t)\,|\,b,c\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q\}
\end{equation}
%
is a group of order $2{(q-1)}^2$.
\end{theorem}\begin{proof} Equality (\ref{eq11}) is a consequence of  equality (\ref{eq10}) and Lemma \ref{lemma4}. So we only need to proof equality (\ref{eq10}).

Following Lemma \ref{lemma4}  we have that transformations  $(\pi (x),\ c(x))=\left(bx,c\right)$ and $\left(bx^{q-2},cx^t\right)$ are automorphisms of the code  $V$. So $P\left(V\right)\supseteq D_{q-1}$. The equality in this inclusion was proved in Lemma \ref{lemma7} for the case $t=1$. If $t\ge q/2-1$, then $J_{V^{\bot }}=\{1,\ 2,\dots ,s\}$, where $2\le s=q-2-t\le (q-2)/2$. By Lemma \ref{lemma1} and Lemma \ref{lemma6} we have  that  $P(V)=P(V^{\bot })=P(U)$, where $U$ is a $C(q-1,\ q)$-code, for which $J_U=\left\{0,\ 1,\ 2,\dots ,s-1\right\}=J_{V^{\bot }}+\{q-2\}$ $({\rm mod}\ q-1)$. Therefore we only need to prove equality (\ref{eq10}) for the case $1<t<q/2-1$. 

Let $k$ and $r$ be a quotient and a remainder of  division  $q-3\ $ by $t$ respectively, that is  $q-3=kt+r$, $0\le r<t$. Using the induction on $t$ we consider two different cases: when $r>0$ and when  $r=0$. 

{\em Case $r>0$.} Let us consider a code $U=V^k\circ V_1$, where $V^k=V\circ \dots \circ V$ is a  $k$-fold component-wise product of the code $V$ by itself, $V_1$ is a code with $J_{V_1}=\{1\}$. We have that 
\[J_U=\{1,\ 2,\ \dots ,kt+1\},  J_{U^{\bot }}=\{0,\ 1,\dots ,\ r\}.\] 
Since $1\le r<t$, then by the induction hypothesis  we have $P\left(U^{\bot }\right)=D_{q-1}$. But then from the sequence of inclusions $D_{q-1}\subseteq P(V)\subseteq P(V^k)\subseteq P(U)\subseteq P(U^{\bot })=D_{q-1}$, which  holds by Lemma \ref{lemma1} and  Lemma \ref{lemma2}, it follows that   $P(V))=D_{q-1}$. 


{\em Case $r=0$} (i.e. $q-3=kt$). Let us consider a code $U=V^k$ and a dual code $U^{\bot }$. Since $J_U=\{0,\ 1,\ \dots ,q-3\}$ and $J_{U^{\bot }}=\{1\}$, then from Lemma \ref{lemma1} and Lemma \ref{lemma5} it follows that automorphisms of the code have the form  

\begin{equation}\label{eq12}
\left(\tau (x),\ \frac{\tau (x)}{ax}\right),\ \tau (x)\in S({{\mathbb F}}^*_q),\ a\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q.\end{equation}
On the other hand, if $(\pi(x),\ c(x))\in {\rm MAut}\left(V\right)$, then by Lemma \ref{lemma2} we have  that

\begin{equation}\label{eq13}
(\pi (x),\ {c(x)}^k)\in {\rm MAut}\left(U\right).
\end{equation}
Comparing equations (\ref{eq12}) and (\ref{eq13}) we conclude that $\pi (x)=ax{c(x)}^k$. 

To ascertain the form of  $\pi (x)$ we use the relations (\ref{eq8}) for $j=0$ and $t$. Namely,
\[c(x)=\sum^t_{i=9}{c_ix^i\in {{\mathbb F}}_q\left[x\right],}\] 
\[a^{-1}{<c(x){\pi (x)}^t>}_{q-1}={<x^t{c(x)}^{q-2}>}_{q-1}=\sum^t_{i=0}{{\delta }_ix^i\in {{\mathbb F}}_q[x]},\] 
where ${<\varphi (x)>}_{q-1}=\varphi (x)\ (\bmod\ x^{q-1}-1)$. The polynomial  $c(x)$ does not have any root in  ${{\mathbb F}}^*_q$.  So ${<{c(x)}^{q-1}>}_{q-1}=1$  and therefore
\[{<x^t{c(x)}^{q-2}c(x)>}_{q-1}=x^t=\left(\sum^t_{i=0}{{\delta }_ix^i}\right)\left(\sum^t_{i=0}{c_ix^i}\right).\] 
The last equation gives the following system of equations with respect to   $c_i$  and ${\delta }_i$:
\begin{equation*}
\left\{ \begin{array}{ccc}
\sum_{i+j=t}{c_i{\delta }_j}&=1,&  \\ 
\sum_{i+j=k}{c_i{\delta }_j}&=0,& 0\le k\le 2t,\ k\ne t.
 \end{array}
\right.
\end{equation*}
Let us solve this system of equations with respect to  $c_i$, sequentially considering the following cases: $c_0\ne 0$; $c_0=0,\ c_1\ne 0$; $c_0=c_1=0,\ c_2\ne 0$; and so on. As a result we have 
\[c(x)=c_mx^m,\  c_m\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q,\ 0\leq m\leq t,\] 
and therefore

\begin{equation*}\label{eq14}
\pi (x)=bx^u,\ b\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q,\ u=km+1,\mbox{ gcd }(u,\ q-1)=1.
\end{equation*}


For specification possible values for $u$ (or $m$) we use the relations that follow from Lemma  \ref{lemma7}:
\[0\le{\deg{{<c(x)\ \pi (x)}^j>}_{q-1}\le t\ },\] 
or
\[0\le{\left\lfloor m+uj\right\rfloor }_{q-1}\le t,\ 1\le j\le t.\] 
Sequentially solving these inequalities, we have: 
\[0\le{\left\lfloor m+u\right\rfloor }_{q-1}\le t\Rightarrow -m\le u\le t-m,\] 
\[0\le{\left\lfloor m+2u\right\rfloor }_{q-1}\le t\Rightarrow -\left[\frac{m}{2}\right]\le u\le \left[\frac{t-m}{2}\right],\] 
\[\dots\] 
\[0\le{\left\lfloor m+tu\right\rfloor }_{q-1}\le t\Rightarrow -\left[\frac{m}{t}\right]\le u\le \left[\frac{t-m}{t}\right]\Longrightarrow -1\le u\le 1.\] 
If $u=0$, then $\pi (x)=b$. Such polynomial is not a permutation polynomial. So  $u\ne 0$ and it remains to consider only two cases: $u=1$ (when $m=0$) and $m=q-2={\left\lfloor -1\right\rfloor }_{q-1}$ (when $m=t$). 

Therefore relation (\ref{eq10}) holds and all automorphisms of the code $V$ are exhausted by transformations (\ref{eq11}). \end{proof}\begin{corollary}\label{seq9} Let $J_V=\{r,\ r+1,\dots ,r+t\}$, $1\le t\le q-3$. Then 
\[{\rm MAut}\left(V\right)=G\equiv \{\left(ax,c\right),\ \left(ax^{q-2},cx^{t+2r}\right)\,|\,a,c\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q\}.\] 
\end{corollary}\begin{proof} Using Lemma \ref{lemma4} we establish that transformations from   $G$ are automorphisms of the code $V$, i.e. $G\subseteq{\rm MAut}\left(V\right)$. In the other hand, $V={RS}_{t,q}\circ g$, $g=(1,\ {\alpha }^r,\ {\alpha }^{2r},\dots ,\ {\alpha }^{(q-2)r})$, i.e. codes $V$ and ${RS}_{t,q}$ are equivalent and their automorphism   groups  are  isomorphic. Since orders of the groups ${\rm MAut}\left({RS}_{t,q}\right)$ and $G$ are equal, then ${\rm MAut}\left(V\right)=G$. \end{proof}\begin{theorem}\label{thm10} Let $1\le t\le q-3$. Then 
\[{\rm MAut}{\rm (}{RS}^e_{t,q})=\{\left(ax+b,c\right)\,|\,a,c\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q,\ b\in {{\mathbb F}}_q\}.\] 
\end{theorem}\begin{proof} Let $V^e$ and $W^e$ be extensions of $C(q-1,q)$-codes $V$ and $W$,  for which $J_V=\{0,\ 1,\dots ,t\}$, $J_W=\{0,\ 1,\dots ,s\}$, where $s=q-2-t$. It is clear that $V^e={RS}^e_{t,q}$, $W^e={RS}^e_{s,q}$, and ${\left(V^e\right)}^{\bot }=W^e$. Therefore we can suppose that $t\le q/2-1$ (otherwise we can consider the code $W^e$ instead of the code  $V^e$). 

Let $(\pi (x),\ c(x))\in {\rm MAut}\left(V^e\right)$,  $d(x)$ be a polynomial that satisfy  the following property

\begin{equation}\label{eq15}
c(x)d(x)\equiv{\rm 1\ (mod}\ x^q-x{\rm )}.
\end{equation}

Then $(\pi (x),\ d(x))\in {\rm MAut}\left(W^e\right)$. From relations (\ref{eq8}), using $j=0$, it follows that
\[c(x)=c_0+c_1x^1+\dots +c_mx^m, m\le t;\] 
\[d(x)=d_0+d_1x^1+\dots +d_rx^r, r\le s.\] 
From relation (\ref{eq15}) it follows that $c(x)=c_0\ne 0$ and $d(x)=d_0\ne 0$  are constant polynomials. It remains to establish the form of the polynomial $\pi (x)$.

From (\ref{eq8}), using $j=1$, it follows that $\pi (x)={\pi }_0+{\pi }_1x^1+\dots +{\pi }_tx^t$. Using the same relations, namely: 
\[{\pi (x)}^j\ \left({\rm mod}\ x^q-x\right)={\delta }^{(j)}_0+{\delta }^{(j)}_1x^1+\dots +{\delta }^{(j)}_tx^t\in {{\mathbb F}}_q[x]\] 
when $j=2,\ 3,\dots ,t$, we sequentially get 
\[{\pi }_t=0,{\rm \ \ }{\pi }_{t-1}=0, \dots , {\pi }_2=0,\] 
i.e. $\pi (x)=ax+b$, $a\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q,\ b\in {{\mathbb F}}_q$. \end{proof}\begin{theorem}\label{thm11} Let $V$ be a $C(q-1,\ q)$-code such that 
\[J_V=\{{\left\lfloor -r\right\rfloor }_{q-1},\ {\left\lfloor -r-1\right\rfloor }_{q-1},\dots ,{\left\lfloor -1\right\rfloor }_{q-1},\ 0,\ 1,\dots ,t\},\] 
where $r$,$\ t\ge 1$; $2(r+t)\le q-4$. Then
\begin{equation}\label{eq16} 
{\rm MAut(}V^e)=\left\{ \begin{array}{ll}
\left\{\left(ax,c\right)|a,c\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q\right\},& \mbox{ if } r\neq t; \\ 
\left\{\left(ax,c\right){\rm ,\ }\left(ax^{q-2},c\right)|a,c\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q\right\},&\mbox{ if }\ r=t. \end{array}
\right.\end{equation}
\end{theorem}\begin{proof} Let $(\pi (x),\ c(x))\in {\rm MAut}(V^e)$. We consider codes $W=V^e\circ$ $V^e$ and $W^{\bot }$. Generator matrices of these codes have the form:
\[G_W=\left( \begin{array}{cc}
1 &  \begin{array}{cc}
