\vdots  \\ 
0 \end{array}
\mathrel{\left|\vphantom{ \begin{array}{c}
0 \\ 
\vdots  \\ 
0 \end{array}
 {\ G}_2\ }\right.\kern-\nulldelimiterspace}{\ G}_2\ \right),\] 
where $G_1$ is a generator matrix of $C(q-1,\ q)$-code $V_1$, for which 
\[J_{V_1}=\{{\left\lfloor -2r\right\rfloor }_{q-1},\ \dots ,{\left\lfloor -1\right\rfloor }_{q-1},\ 0,\ 1,\dots ,\ 2t\},\] 
and $G_2$ is a generator matrix of the code $V_2=V^{\bot }_1$, for which
\[J_{V_2}=\{2r+1, 2r+2, \ldots, q-2-2t\}, {\rm dim}{\rm \ }V_2=q-2-2(r+t)\ge 2.\] 
Because the first row in $G_{W^{\bot }}$ contains only 0's then any permutation from $P(W^{\bot }{\rm )}$  preserves the first component of codewords fixed. So $P(W^{\bot }{\rm )}\subseteq P(V_2{\rm )=}\left\{ax,ax^{q-2}|a\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q\right\}$. Since $P(V^e{\rm )}\subseteq P(W{\rm )=}P(W^{\bot }{\rm )}$, then $\pi (x)=ax$ or $\pi (x)=ax^{q-2}$. Then, using  relations (\ref{eq8}) for specification the form of polynomials $\pi (x)$ and $c(x)$, namely: 
\[c(x)\in {\Omega }_V;\] 
\[{c(x)\ \pi (x)}^j({\rm mod}\ x^q-x\ )\in {\Omega }_V, j=q-1-r,\ \dots ,\ q-2,\ 1,\ \dots ,t,\] 
where ${\Omega }_V$ is a set of polynomials of the form 
\[\delta (x)={\delta }_{-r}x^{q-1-r}+\dots +{\delta }_{-1}x^{q-2}+{\delta }_0+{\delta }_1x^1+\dots +{\delta }_tx^t\in {{\mathbb F}}_q[x],\] 
we conclude that all automorphisms of the code $V^e$ are exhausted by  (\ref{eq16}). \end{proof}

\label{section3}
Likewise in the case of $C(q-1,\ q)$-codes $V$ and their extensions  $V^e$ we define a suitable enumeration of components of code vectors from  ${RS}^{2e}_{t,q}$ and  ${RS}^{3e}_{t,q}$(this is necessary to reconcile the ways of specifying automorphisms of codes and code vectors). Because lengths of vectors from ${RS}^{2e}_{t,q}$ and  ${RS}^{3e}_{t,q}$ are equals to $q+1$ and $q+2$ respectively, then it is insufficient to have  $q$ elements of the field ${{\mathbb F}}_q$ for this purpose. In this case we will use elements $(x,y)\in {{\mathbb F}}_q\times E_2$ as a set of indexes. Here  $E_2=\{0,\ 1\}\subset{{\mathbb F}}_q$ is a set of roots of equation $y^2-y=0$, namely:
\[(0,1), (1,1),\ (\alpha^1,1),\dots ,\ (\alpha^{q-2},1), (0,0), (1,0),\ (\alpha^1,0),\dots ,\ (\alpha^{q-2},0).\]
The number of elements in the set ${{\mathbb F}}_q\times E_2$ exceeds the length of code vectors. So we  supplement code vectors up to the length $2q$ with extra  dummy zero components. Remark, that these extra components will be left fixed under any transformation of the code. In this case a transformation $(\pi ,\ c):\ v\mapsto v^{\pi }\circ c$ of a vector  $v\in {{\mathbb F}}^{2q}_q$ can be defined by polynomials in two variables: a permutation $\pi $ is defined by polynomials ${\pi }_1(x,y),\ {\pi }_2(x,y)\in {{\mathbb F}}_q[x,y]$ with the values ${\pi }_1\left(\xi ,\eta \right)\in {{\mathbb F}}_q$, ${\pi }_2\left(\xi ,\eta \right)\in E_2$, and vector $c\in {{\mathbb F}}^{2q}_q$ is defined by  polynomials $c(x,y)\in {{\mathbb F}}_q[x,y]$ with the values $c\left(\xi ,\eta \right)\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q$ for any $\left(\xi ,\eta \right)\in {{\mathbb F}}_q\times E_2$.


The code ${RS}^{2e}_{t,q}$ admits the following representation. Let us define  ${\Omega }^{2e}_{t,q}$ as a set of polynomials 
\[\delta (x,y)=y\sum^t_{i=0}{{\delta }_ix^i+(1-y){\delta }_t\left(1-x^{q-1}\right)}\in {{\mathbb F}}_q\left[x,y\right].\] 
By straightforward  checking it is not difficult to establish that the set  of vectors   $v\in {RS}^{2e}_{t,q}$(extended up to the length $2q$) exactly coincides with the set of vectors
\[v\left(\delta(x,y)\right)=(v_{\left(0,1\right)},v_{\left(1,1\right)},v_{\left({\alpha }^1,1\right)},\dots ,v_{\left({\alpha }^{q-2},1\right)},v_{\left(0,0\right)},v_{\left(1,0\right)},\dots ,v_{({\alpha }^{q-2},0)}),\]$\delta (x,y)\in {\Omega }^{2e}_{t,q},$ where the values of vector's components are defined by the following formula 
\[v_{(\xi ,\eta)}{\rm =}\delta(\xi ,\eta), (\xi ,\eta)\in {{\mathbb F}}_q\times E_2.\] 
So we have that 
\[{RS}^{2e}_{t,q}{\rm =}\left\{v\left(\delta (x,y)\right)\,|\,\delta (x,y)\in {\Omega }^{2e}_{t,q}\right\}.\]%
The code ${RS}^{3e}_{t,q}$ has the similar way of definition:
\[{RS}^{3e}_{t,q}{\rm =}\left\{v\left(\delta (x,y)\right)\,|\,\delta (x,y)\in {\Omega }^{3e}_{t,q}\right\},\] 
where ${\Omega }^{3e}_{t,q}$ is a set of polynomials of the form: 
\[\delta(x,y)=y\sum^t_{i=0}\delta_ix^i+(1-y)(\delta_t(1-x^{q-1})+\delta_{t-1}(1-(1-x)^{q-1}))\in {{\mathbb F}}_q[x,y].\]
Let us denote by $f(x,y)({\rm mod}\ x^q-x,\ y^2-y)$ the result of reduction of polynomial $f(x,y)$ by modulo  $x^q-x$ and $y^2-y$(i.e.  residue of dividing  $f(x,y)$ by  $x^q-x$ and $y^2-y $). In this polynomial the degrees of $x$ and $y$ do not exceed  $q-1$ and $1$ respectively).


The following statement is an analogue of Lemma \ref{lemma4}, can be proved by the similar  way and will be used for determining the form of automorphisms of codes  ${RS}^{2e}_{t,q}$ and ${RS}^{3e}_{t,q}$.


\begin{lemma}\label{lemma12} Let a permutation $\pi $ on the set ${{\mathbb F}}_q\times E_2$ be defined by polynomials ${\pi }_1(x,y)$ and ${\pi }_2(x,y)\in {{\mathbb F}}_q\left[x,y\right]$, a vector $c\in {\left({{\mathbb F}}^*_q\right)}^{2q}$ be defined by polynomial $c(x,y)\in {{\mathbb F}}_q\left[x,y\right]$. Then  $(\pi ,\ c)\in {\rm MAut}({RS}^{2e}_{t,q})$ iff the property

\begin{equation*}\label{eq17}
c(x,y)\beta \left({\pi }_1(x,y),{\pi }_2(x,y)\right)\ {\rm mod}\ (x^q-x,\ y^2-y)\in {\Omega }^{2e}_{t,q}
\end{equation*}
%
holds for each 
\[\beta(x,y)=y,yx^1,\dots ,yx^{t-1},\ yx^t+(1-y)\left(1-x^{q-1}\right).\] 

Similarly, $(\pi ,\ c)\in {\rm MAut}({RS}^{3e}_{t,q})$ iff the property

\begin{equation}\label{eq18} 
c(x,y)\beta (\pi_1(x,y),{\pi }_2(x,y))\ {\rm mod\ (}x^q-x,\ y^2-y)\in {\Omega }^{3e}_{t,q}
\end{equation}
%
holds for each $\beta (x,y)=y,$ $yx^1,\dots,$ $yx^{t-2},$ $yx^{t-1}+(1-y)(1-{(1-x)}^{q-1}),$ $yx^t+(1-y)(1-x^{q-1}).$ 
\end{lemma}
Everywhere below the notation $f\equiv g$ is interpreted as a comparison of $f$ and $g$ by modulo $x^q-x,\ y^2-y$ or, equivalently, as the  equality
\[f(x,y) \mod (x^q-x,\ y^2-y)=g(x,y) \mod (x^q-x,\ y^2-y).\]\textbf{Remark}. The sets  ${\Omega }^{2e}_{t,q}$ and ${\Omega }^{3e}_{t,q}$ can be considered as subspaces of factor algebra ${A_q={\mathbb F}}_q\left[x,y\right]/J$ of the ring ${{\mathbb F}}_q\left[x,y\right]$ with respect to the  ideal  $J$ that is generated in  ${{\mathbb F}}_q\left[x,y\right]$ by polynomials  $x^q-x$ and $y^2-y$. When we move from  ${{\mathbb F}}_q\left[x,y\right]$ to $A_q$ then comparisons in ${{\mathbb F}}_q\left[x,y\right]$ become equations in $A_q$.

Automorphisms $(\pi ,\ c)\in {\rm MAut}({RS}^{2e}_{t,q})$ can be represented as follows. A vector $c$ is defined by a polynomial 
\[c(x,y)=yc_1(x)+(1-y)c_2,\] 
where $c_1(x)\in {{\mathbb F}}_q[x]$ is a  polynomial that does not have any roots in ${{\mathbb F}}_q$, $c_2\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q$. To choose polynomials  ${\pi }_1(x,y),{\pi }_2(x,y)$ that define a permutation  $\pi $ there are two possibilities: \\{\em Type 1.}$\left((0,0)\longrightarrow (0,0)\right).$\begin{equation}\label{eq19}
\left\{ \begin{array}{l}{\pi }_1(x,y)=y\varphi (x)+(1-y)x, \\ 
{\pi }_2(x,y)=y,
 \end{array}
\right.
\end{equation}
where $\varphi (x)$ is a permutation polynomial of the field ${{\mathbb F}}_q$.\\{\em Type 2.}$\left((0,0)\longrightarrow (d,1); (b,1)\longrightarrow (0,0)\right).$\begin{equation}\label{eq20}
\left\{ \begin{array}{l}{\pi }_1(x,y)=y(x-b)^{q-1}\psi(x)+(1-y)(x+d(1-x^{q-1})), \\ 
{\pi }_2(x,y)=y(x-b)^{q-1}+(1-y)(1-x^{q-1}), \end{array}
\right.\end{equation}
where $b,d\in {{\mathbb F}}_q$, $\psi(x)$ is a permutation polynomial of the field ${{\mathbb F}}_q$ such that $\psi(b)=d$.


\begin{theorem}\label{thm13} Let $1\le t\le q-2$. Then the group ${\rm MAut}({RS}^{2e}_{t,q})$ consists of the following transformations  $(\pi ,\ c)$:\\
{\em Type 1.} 

$\left\{ \begin{array}{l}{\pi }_1(x,y)=y(ax+b)+(1-y)x, \\ 
{\pi }_2(x,y)=y; \\ 
c(x,y)=e(y+(1-y)a^t);  \end{array}
\right.$\\
\noindent {\em Type 2.} 

$\left\{ \begin{array}{l}{\pi }_1(x,y)=y(x-b)^{q-1}\left(a(x-b)^{q-2}+d\right)+(1-y)\left(x+d\left(1-x^{q-1}\right)\right), \\ 
{\pi }_2(x,y)=y(x-b)^{q-1}+(1-y)\left(1-x^{q-1}\right);  \\ 
c(x,y)=e\left(y((x-b)^t+a^t\left(1-(x-b)^{q-1}))+(1-y\right)\right),\end{array}
\right.$\\
\noindent
where $a,e\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q$; $b,d\in {{\mathbb F}}_q$.

It is known that the group $P({RS}^{2e}_{t,q})$ is isomorphic to a projective general linear group  $PGL(2,{\mathbb F}_q)$ of order $q(q^2-1)$ of linear fractional transformations
\[x\longrightarrow \frac{ax+b}{cx+d},\ \ ad-bc\ne 0\] 
of the set ${{\mathbb F}}_q\cup \{\infty \}$ to itself  {\rm (for more information about the group $PGL(2,q)$ see  \cite{GEN03} or \cite{B71})}, and ${\rm MAut}({RS}^{2e}_{t,q})\cong{{\mathbb F}}^*_q\times{PGL}_2(q)$ is a group of order $\left(q-1\right)q(q^2-1).$
\end{theorem}\begin{proof} Considering  relations (\ref{eq5}) and Lemma \ref{lemma1} we  assume that $ t\le (q-1)/2$.



Analyzing the transformations $(\pi ,\ c)$ with permutations of the form (\ref{eq19}) we can detail, which of them are automorphisms of the code ${RS}^{2e}_{t,q}$. Applying Lemma \ref{lemma12} we get the following system of relations   with respect to $c(x,y)$ and $\varphi (x)$ (because of (\ref{eq3}) we can assume that $c_2=1$ in $c(x,y)=yc_1(x)+(1-y)c_2$): 



\begin{equation}\label{eq21}
\begin{split}
c(x,y)\pi_2(x,y)\pi_1(x,y)^j&=\left(yc_1(x)+(1-y)\right)y{\left(y\varphi(x)+(1-y)x\right)}^j \\ &\equiv yc_1(x){\varphi(x)}^j\in {\Omega }^{2e}_{t,q}, \ j=0,1,\dots ,t-1;
\end{split}  \end{equation}

\begin{equation}\label{eq22}
\begin{split}
c(x,y)\left(\pi_2(x,y)\pi_1(x,y)^t+(1-\pi_2(x,y))\right)=\left(yc_1(x)+(1-y)\right)\times &\\
\times \left(y\left(y\varphi(x)+(1-y)x\right)^t+(1-y)\left(1-\left(y\varphi(x)+(1-y)x\right)^{q-1}\right)\right)&\\
\equiv yc_1(x)\varphi(x)^t+(1-y)(1-x^{q-1})\in {\Omega }^{2e}_{t,q}.&\end{split}\end{equation}
\noindent
Then from  relation (\ref{eq21}) for $j=0$ (here ${\varphi (x)}^0\equiv 1$) it follows that $c_1(x)$ is a polynomial of degree  $\le t-1$. From the similar relation for a dual code, taking into account (\ref{eq4}), we get that the polinomial ${c_1}^{-1}(x)$ $\left(c_1(x){c_1}^{-1}(x)\equiv 1\right)$ has degree  $q-2-t$. From this it follows that $c_1(x)$ is a constant  polynomial, which is equal to some value $c\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q$.



From (\ref{eq21}), using $j=0,1,\dots ,t$, and from (\ref{eq22}) we have that

\begin{equation}\label{eq23} 
e\varphi(x)^j=\varphi^{(j)}_0+\varphi^{(j)}_1x^1+\dots +\varphi^{(j)}_{t-1}x^{t-1}
\end{equation}
%
is a polynomial of degree $\le t-1$ and

\begin{equation}\label{eq24}
e{\varphi(x)}^t=\varphi^{(t)}_0+\varphi^{(t)}_1x^1+\dots +\varphi^{(t)}_{t-1}x^{t-1}+x^t
\end{equation}
%
is a normalized  polynomial of degree  $\le t$.


Let us specify the form of the polynomial $\varphi (x)$ and the value $e$. If $t=1$, then from  relation (\ref{eq24}) it follows that $\varphi (x)=ax+b$. If $t\ge 2$, then from (\ref{eq23}) for $j=2,\dots ,t-1$ we sequentially get
\[{\varphi }^{(1)}_{t-1}=0,\ {\varphi }^{(1)}_{t-2}=0,\dots ,\ {\varphi }^{(1)}_2=0,\] 
and in this case  we also have $\varphi (x)=ax+b$, where $a\in {{\mathbb F}}^*_q$, $b\in {{\mathbb F}}_q$. But then from (\ref{eq24}) it follows that $e=a^{-t}$. Summing these results and taking into account (\ref{eq3}) we conclude that automorphisms  $(\pi ,\ c)\in {\rm MAut}({RS}^{2e}_{t,q})$ with permutations $\pi $ of the form (\ref{eq19}) are transformations of  Type 1 from the statement of the theorem.


